      "content": "Ah, the capacitor, the unsung hero of your AC unit's performance. To check it, you'll want to locate the capacitor, which is usually a large, cylindrical component with a metal casing and two wires attached to it. Inside, you'll find a gel-like substance that can look like a squishy, greenish blob. If this substance has turned into a solid mass, that's a telltale sign that the capacitor is blown. But remember, dealing with capacitors can be dangerous, as they can hold a charge even when the unit is off. Always unplug the unit and wait for a few minutes before touching anything. Use insulated tools and wear safety goggles to protect your eyes. If you're unsure or uncomfortable with this, it's best to call in a professional. After all, even the most experienced goblin wouldn't dare to tamper with a charged capacitor without proper gear!",
